### Generic Functions â€” Scoping Rules (Critical)

hica's type inference is **file-scoped in test mode**: all top-level `fun` declarations and `main()` share one inference context. Only `test` blocks are independent from each other.

**Consequence**: you CANNOT have `fun main()` and multi-type generic tests in the same file.

| Scenario | Works? |
|----------|--------|
| `test` block uses `id(42)`, different `test` block uses `id("hello")` | âś“ Each test block is independent |
| Same `test` block uses `id(42)` and `id("hello")` | âś“ Works |
| `fun main()` uses `id(42)`, `test` block uses `id("hello")` | âś— Fails in `hica test` mode |
| `fun main()` uses `id(42)` and `id("hello")` in sequence | âś— Fails â€” locked to `int` after first call |
| Helper `fun use_int() => id(42)` + `fun use_str() => id("hello")` | âś— Fails â€” top-level funs share context |

**The correct pattern**: Omit `main()` entirely from files with multi-type generic tests. Put usage examples in a separate file that uses only one concrete type per function in `main()`.

```hica
// generic_tests.hc â€” NO main(), only test blocks
fun id(x) => x

test "int" { assert(id(42) == 42) }
test "string" { assert(id("hello") == "hello") }
```

```hica
// generic_usage.hc â€” one type per generic call in main
fun id(x) => x

fun main() {
  let n = id(42)          // only ever used as int in this file
  println(n)
}
```

