### Pipe Operator and Dot-Call Syntax

`|>` and `.f()` are two equivalent ways to chain functions left to right:

```hica
fun main() {
  // Pipe style
  let a = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
    |> filter((x) => x % 2 == 0)
    |> map((x) => x * 10)
    |> fold(0, (acc, x) => acc + x)
  println(a)

  // Dot-call style (same result)
  let b = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
    .filter((x) => x % 2 == 0)
    .map((x) => x * 10)
    .fold(0, (acc, x) => acc + x)
  println(b)
}
```

`a |> f` and `a.f()` both desugar to `f(a)`. Dot-call accepts extra arguments: `a.f(b)` becomes `f(a, b)`.

Rule of thumb:
- Use `|>` for single-argument steps: `5 |> double |> inc`
- Use `.f()` when passing extra arguments: `nums.filter((x) => x > 2).map((x) => x * 10)`

