| `let (a, b) = result_expr` â€” destructuring a result as a tuple | `result<(a,b), e>` is a `result`, not a tuple. You cannot destructure it with `let (a, b) = ...`. Use `match result_expr { Ok((a, b)) => ..., Err(e) => Err(e) }` instead. This mistake often appears alongside the `return` pitfall: `let (v, pos) = match foo() { Ok(p) => bar(p), Err(e) => return Err(e) }` â€” both the `return` and the outer `let (v, pos)` destructuring are wrong. |
| `"a" ++ "b"` | `"a" + "b"` |
| `str(n)` | `show(n)` |
| `else { () }` | `else { }` |
| `my-variable` | `my_variable` |
| `assert(x \|> f == val)` | `let r = x \|> f; assert(r == val)` |
| `assert(match ...)` | `let r = match ...; assert(r == ...)` |
| `items[i]` (list index) | recursive pattern match |
| `let rec aux(x) = ... in aux(start)` (local recursive function) | hica has NO local recursive functions and NO `let ... in` syntax. Every recursive helper must be a top-level `fun`. Pass all needed state as explicit arguments. This is the single most common mistake when generating parsers or tree traversals. |
| inner `fun` closing over outer param for recursion | pass state as an explicit accumulator argument to a top-level helper |
| `(j, _) =>` tuple destructuring in a lambda param | NOT supported â€” same rule as `fun swap((a,b))`. Destructure in the body: `(pair) => { match pair { (j, _) => j } }` |
