| `r \|> and_then_result((x) => ...)` when `r` is `maybe<T>` | `and_then_result` is for `result<T,E>` only. For `maybe<T>`, use `and_then(m, (x) => ...)` or `m \|> and_then((x) => ...)`. Using `and_then_result` on a `maybe` is a type error. Functions like `json_str`, `json_array`, `json_get`, `parse_int`, `parse_float`, `head` all return `maybe<T>` â€” chain them with `and_then`, not `and_then_result`. |
| `map_result(plain_value, f)` where `plain_value` is not a `result<T,E>` | `map_result` takes a `result<T,E>` as its first argument. Calling `map_result(head_or(xs, default), f)` fails because `head_or` returns `T`, not `result<T,E>`. If you want to map a plain value, just call `f(value)` directly or use `let x = head_or(xs, default); f(x)`. |
| `match r { Ok(v) => v, Err(e) => Err(e) }` where the intent is to "unwrap or re-wrap" | `Ok(v) => v` returns `T` (the unwrapped value), while `Err(e) => Err(e)` returns `result<T,E>` â€” the two branches have different types and the match fails to typecheck. If `r` is already a `result` and you want to propagate it unchanged, just use `r` directly. If you want to transform the `Ok` case, use `map_result(r, (v) => ...)`. If you want to propagate errors in a chain, use `and_then_result`. Never write a match just to echo the two constructors back. |
| `json_get(j, "")` or `json_get(j, "key")` on a non-object `Json` value | `json_get` does object key lookup â€” it returns `None` when `j` is anything other than `JObject(...)`. To extract a top-level string, use `json_str(j)` directly. For a top-level array, use `json_array(j)`. For a top-level number, use `json_num(j)`. Only use `json_get` when `j` is an object and you want a field by name. |
| `unwrap_or(maybe_value, default)` on a `maybe<T>` | `unwrap_or` is for `result<T,E>` (returns the value if `Ok`, or `default` if `Err`). For `maybe<T>`, use `unwrap_maybe_or(m, default)`. Using `unwrap_or` on a `maybe` is a type error. Pattern: `json_get(j, "k") \|> and_then(json_str) \|> unwrap_maybe_or("default")`. |
| `expr \|> match { Ok(x) => ..., Err(e) => ... }` | `match` requires a scrutinee â€” you cannot pipe directly into a bare `match` block. Write it as `match expr { Ok(x) => ..., Err(e) => ... }`. |
| `starts_with(s, " \t\n\r")` to check for whitespace | Checks for the literal 4-character string `" \t\n\r"`, not any whitespace character. Use separate `starts_with` calls: `starts_with(s, " ") \|\| starts_with(s, "\t") \|\| starts_with(s, "\n") \|\| starts_with(s, "\r")`. |
| Calling `id(42)` then `id("hello")` in the same function | Type inference monomorphizes within a single `fun` or `main` body: `id` locks to `int` at first call. However, each `test` block has its own independent scope, so calling `id(42)` and `id("hello")` in the *same test block* is valid. Never mix types within one `fun main()`. |
| Using a generic function in `main()` with one type AND in a test block with a different type | In `hica test` mode, all test blocks and `main()` share ONE type inference context. `swap(("a","b"))` in main constrains swap for ALL test blocks too. **Fix: omit `main()` from files that test generic functions across multiple types.** Put the usage example in a separate `.hc` file, or keep all types consistent across the whole file. `hica check` is more permissive and may not catch this. |
| Using helper functions like `fun demo_int() => id(42)` and `fun demo_str() => id("hello")` to work around monomorphism | Does NOT work â€” named top-level functions in the same file share the same inference context. `id` still gets locked to `int`. **Only `test` blocks get independent type inference scopes.** To test a generic with multiple types, use separate test blocks. |
| Calling `id(10)` then `id("hello")` in `main()` in a "separate" usage file | Still fails â€” `main()` is a top-level function and shares the file's inference context. `id` locks to `int` on the first call. **A generic function can only be used with ONE concrete type within a single `fun main()` body.** Split into multiple files if you need both. |
| `hica check` showing `[IO]` effect signatures | `hica check` reports only error count and top-level effects e.g. `[<console, fsys>]` â€” it does NOT print per-function effect types |

